️ What is DSA (Data Structures and Algorithms)?
->DSA stands for Data Structures and Algorithms — it’s the foundation of writing efficient and optimized code.
->A Data Structure is a way of organizing and storing data so it can be accessed and modified efficiently.
    Examples: Arrays, Linked Lists, Stacks, Queues, Trees, Graphs, HashMaps.
->Data Structures help manage data efficiently, while Algorithms help process that data effectively.
->For example, choosing between a HashMap (O(1)) and a List (O(n)) for searching can make a huge difference in speed.
->An algorithm is a step-by-step set of instructions used to solve a problem or perform a specific task.
  While data structures store and organize data, algorithms define how to process that data efficiently.

🧩 Types of Data Structures
Data Structures are mainly divided into two types — Linear and Non-Linear.
=>Linear Data Structures:
Data elements are arranged sequentially (one after another).
Traversal happens in a single level (one direction).
Examples:
 Array – fixed-size structure storing elements in contiguous memory.
 Linked List – nodes connected using pointers.
 Stack – follows LIFO (Last In, First Out).
 Queue – follows FIFO (First In, First Out).

=>Non-Linear Data Structures:
Data elements are arranged in a hierarchical or connected way.
Traversal can happen in multiple directions.
Examples:
 Tree – hierarchical structure (used in databases, XML parsing).
 Graph – set of nodes and edges (used in networks, shortest path).
 Map-Key Value pair
Linear = one-to-one relationship; Non-linear = one-to-many or many-to-many.

⚙️ When to Use Linear vs Non-Linear Data Structures
->Linear Data Structures are used when data needs to be processed sequentially, one element after
->Non-Linear Data Structures are used when data has hierarchical or network-like relationships.

🌍 Real-Time Scenarios of Linear and Non-Linear Data Structures
=>Linear Data Structures – Real-Time Example:
Imagine a food delivery app (like Swiggy or Zomato) showing your order history — the orders are listed one after another in order (latest to oldest).
This uses a List or Queue, where data is processed sequentially — first order, second order, and so on.
Another example: Undo/Redo feature in editors uses a Stack (LIFO) structure.

==>Non-Linear Data Structures – Real-Time Example:
A file system on your computer (folders inside folders) is a perfect example of a Tree structure — root → subfolders → files.
A social network (like LinkedIn or Facebook) uses a Graph to show connections — each user is a node, and relationships are edges.

