⏱ What is Time Complexity?
Time Complexity is the measure of how much time an algorithm takes to run as the size of input increases.
It helps us analyze the performance of an algorithm without actually running it.
It is usually expressed in Big O notation (e.g., O(1), O(n), O(log n), O(n²)).
It doesn’t measure real “clock time” — it measures the number of basic operations the algorithm performs.
Example:
A for loop running n times → O(n).
A nested loop → O(n²).
A binary search → O(log n).

💾 What is Space Complexity?
Space Complexity is the amount of memory an algorithm uses while executing.
It includes memory for variables, data structures, input values, recursion stack, and temporary storage.
It helps analyze how efficiently an algorithm uses memory as input size (n) increases.
Example:
int sum = 0;      // uses constant space → O(1)
int[] arr = new int[n]; // uses extra memory for n elements → O(n)

The space complexity of this code is O(n) because the array grows with input size, while variables use constant memory.


