1)Why is Binary Search Not Suitable for Linked Lists?
  Binary Search requires direct access to the middle element. In a LinkedList, there is no index-based access, so we must traverse nodes one by one.
  Finding the middle node takes O(n) time. Therefore, Binary Search loses its advantage and becomes less efficient than expected.

2)Stack and queue.
    Stack and Queue are both linear data structures used to store and manage data, but they differ in the order in which elements are processed.
    Stack
    Stack follows the LIFO (Last In, First Out) principle.
    The last element inserted is the first element removed.
    Main operations:
    push() → Insert element
    pop() → Remove element
    peek() → View top element
    Example:
    Push: 10, 20, 30

    Top
     |
    30
    20
    10

    Pop() => 30

    Queue
    Queue follows the FIFO (First In, First Out) principle.
    The first element inserted is the first element removed.
    Main operations:
    offer()/add() → Insert element
    poll()/remove() → Remove element
    peek() → View front element
    Example:
    Front          Rear
      |              |
     10 -> 20 -> 30

    Poll() => 10

3)What Causes Hash Collision?
  Hash Collision occurs when two different keys generate the same hash value and are stored in the same bucket.
  HashMap handles collisions using LinkedList and, in Java 8+, converts heavily populated buckets into Red-Black Trees.
  Good hashCode implementations help reduce collisions.

  Example:
  key1.hashCode() == key2.hashCode()

4)Difference Between HashSet, LinkedHashSet, and TreeSet
 HashSet, LinkedHashSet, and TreeSet all store unique elements, but they differ in ordering.
 HashSet does not maintain any order and provides the best performance.
 LinkedHashSet maintains insertion order while still offering near O(1) performance.
 TreeSet stores elements in sorted order using a Red-Black Tree and has O(log n) performance.
 Both HashSet and LinkedHashSet allow one null value, whereas TreeSet does not.
 Choose HashSet for speed, LinkedHashSet for insertion order, and TreeSet for sorted data.

