10)How Do You Detect a Cycle in a Linked List?
  A cycle in a linked list can be detected using Floyd's Cycle Detection Algorithm.
  Two pointers, slow and fast, start from the head. The slow pointer moves one step at a time, while the fast pointer moves two steps.
  If a cycle exists, the fast pointer eventually catches the slow pointer and both meet at the same node.
  If the fast pointer reaches null, no cycle exists. This approach takes O(n) time and O(1) space, making it the most efficient solution.

simple code
public boolean hasCycle(ListNode head) {

    ListNode slow = head;
    ListNode fast = head;

    while (fast != null && fast.next != null) {

        slow = slow.next;
        fast = fast.next.next;

        if (slow == fast) {
            return true;
        }
    }

    return false;
}

11)When Would You Use Merge Sort Over Quick Sort?
  Merge Sort is preferred when stable sorting is required, when sorting linked lists, or when guaranteed O(n log n) performance is needed.
  It is also commonly used for external sorting where data is too large to fit into memory.
  Merge Sort always provides O(n log n) time complexity but requires O(n) extra space.
  Quick Sort is generally faster for arrays because of better cache performance and lower memory usage.
  However, its worst-case time complexity is O(n²). Therefore, Merge Sort is chosen for stability and predictable performance,
  while Quick Sort is preferred for fast in-memory array sorting.

  Merge Sort
  = Stable
  = Linked List
  = Guaranteed O(n log n)

  Quick Sort
  = Faster for Arrays
  = Less Memory
  = Average O(n log n)

12)Which Data Structure Would You Use for Caching?
 For caching, a HashMap is commonly used because it provides O(1) average-time lookup, insertion, and deletion.
 This allows frequently accessed data to be retrieved quickly without querying the database repeatedly.
 In real-world applications, cache size is limited, so an LRU (Least Recently Used) cache is often implemented using a combination of a HashMap and a Doubly Linked List.
 The HashMap provides fast lookups, while the Doubly Linked List maintains the order of recently accessed items.
 In Java, LinkedHashMap can be used to implement an LRU cache efficiently.

