15)What is BFS (Breadth First Search)? How it works internally?
  Breadth First Search (BFS) is a traversal algorithm used for trees and graphs.
  It visits nodes level by level, starting from the root or source node.
  BFS uses a Queue data structure to maintain the order of nodes to be processed.
  First, the root node is added to the queue. Then nodes are removed one by one, visited, and their neighbors or children are added to the queue.
  This process continues until the queue becomes empty. BFS has O(n) time complexity and is commonly used to find the shortest path in an unweighted graph.

  BFS uses a Queue (FIFO) internally.
  Example Tree
            1
          /   \
         2     3
        / \   / \
       4  5  6   7

  BFS Traversal
  1 → 2 → 3 → 4 → 5 → 6 → 7

  Time Complexity
  For n nodes:
  Time  : O(n)
  Space : O(n)

16)What is DFS (Depth First Search)? How it will work internally?
  Depth First Search (DFS) is a traversal algorithm used for trees and graphs that explores a path as deep as possible before backtracking.
  It uses a Stack data structure, either explicitly or through recursion.
  Starting from the root node, DFS visits a node, then recursively visits its children until it reaches a leaf node.
  After that, it backtracks and explores other branches. DFS has O(n) time complexity because each node is visited once.
  It is commonly used in tree traversals, path finding, cycle detection, and graph problems.

  Example Tree
            1
          /   \
         2     3
        / \   / \
       4  5  6   7

    DFS Traversal (Preorder)
    1 → 2 → 4 → 5 → 3 → 6 → 7

    Time & Space Complexity
    For n nodes:
    Time  : O(n)
    Space : O(n)

17)What is a Heap?
A Heap is a Complete Binary Tree that follows a special ordering property.
In a Max Heap, the parent node is greater than or equal to its children, while in a Min Heap, the parent node is smaller than or equal to its children.
Heaps are commonly used to implement Priority Queues because they allow quick access to the highest or lowest priority element.
Internally, heaps are usually stored in arrays rather than using tree nodes. Insert and delete operations take O(log n) time due to heapify operations,
while accessing the root element takes O(1) time. In Java, the PriorityQueue class is implemented using a heap.

Types of Heap
1. Max Heap
In a Max Heap:
Parent >= Children
Largest element is always at the root.
Example:

         100
        /   \
      80     70
     / \    / \
   40 50  30 20

Root contains the maximum value.

2. Min Heap
In a Min Heap:
Parent <= Children
Smallest element is always at the root.
Example:

          10
        /    \
      20      30
     / \     / \
   40 50   60 70

18)What is a Spanning Tree?
  A Spanning Tree is a subgraph of a connected graph that includes all vertices and connects them without forming any cycles.
  It contains exactly V−1 edges, where V is the number of vertices in the graph.
  A graph can have multiple spanning trees. The main purpose of a spanning tree is to connect all nodes using the minimum number of edges while avoiding loops.
  Spanning trees are commonly used in network design, routing, and communication systems.
  If the graph is weighted, the spanning tree with the minimum total weight is called a Minimum Spanning Tree (MST).

